<TABLE WIDTH='100%' BORDER='0' CELLPADDING='5' CELLSPACING='0'><TR><TD WIDTH='*' VALIGN='top'><P><P><span class='h1'><h2><b>Time  to challenge</b></h2></span><BR><P><B></B><P>11/20/2007<P>With Supreme Court (SC) Chief Justice Reynato Puno coming out with a statement that the executive privilege being invoked by the executive branch can be challenged by the legislature before the high court, on grounds of grave abuse, that should be more than a cue for the Senate, as a body, to challenge Malacañang this issue, and probably win the case.<P>Why the Senate hasn’t quite moved to bring this matter to the high court is perplexing, given the fact that its various probes get stonewalled every single time on account of Malacañang’s facile claim of executive privilege barring Palace officials from attending these hearings.<P>After all, it is as clear as day that the hearings have nothing to do with the essence of national security, since most of the Senate probes focus on corruption, and other criminal activities that are meant to make the executive accountable to the people, which is mandated by the Constitution.<P>That Malacañang uses this executive privilege to shield  its occupants in covering up for their criminal activities has become much too clear.<P>During Gloria Arroyo’s  earlier stay in the Palace, with both the Senate and the House under her full control, owing to the fact that her allies were in the majority, there was never an invocation of this privilege, even when there were ongoing congressional probes, as she and her Palace aides were guaranteed protection by her congressional allies, despite the evidence presented as it was the senator-allies who were doing the stonewalling, to protect Gloria and her aides.<P>As for the SC, it, too, served to protect her, constantly ruling in Malacañang’s favor and even giving her that big opening to inoculate herself from impeachment proceedings year after year through that ruling of the first impeachment complaint filed being the only complaint that is deemed valid for the year.<P>The fact alone that surveys showed the big erosion of public confidence in the high court, along with then Chief Justice Hilario Davide Jr. becoming the most unpopular judiciary head, already pointed to the fact that Filipinos saw the high court as highly partisan toward Gloria and Malacañang.<P>Things came to a head in 2005, after the tapped conversations between Gloria and then Commission on Elections Commissioner Virgilio “Garci” Garcillano that pointed to vote rigging operations were exposed and where a Palace cover-up was clearly seen by the people. <P>With some senator-allies having called for her resignation, the Senate started on its “independent” path. It was also then that not only executive privilege was being invoked, but also the issuance of the presidential gag order, both of which served to stonewall any and all congressional probes.<P>But it was also the challenge to Executive Order 464, the gag order, that opened the door for Malacañang to abuse its executive privilege, even when the ruling stated when the executive branch could invoke this privilege, on inquiries such as the Question Hour, which is a rare occurrence, but which Malacañang managed to keep on invoking in every legislative hearing to evade public accountability.<P>This has become a farce, as even the military also ow  invokes executive privilege along with the presidential gag orders on claimed grounds of national security.<P>Thus, the Jocelyn “Joc-Joc” Bolante P3-billion fertilizer funds scam is at a standstill, despite this being submitted by the Senate to the Ombudsman for action. Thus, the sanitized Mayuga Report absolving the military generals of any and all participation in the 2004 presidential vote-rigging operations was never made public. Thus, there is continued stonewalling on the part of Malacañang in the Senate probes into the ZTE-National Broadband Network project, along with the Palace’s “cash gifts” to congressmen and local executives, and any other hearings, save for the budget hearings, where the Cabinet officials have to appear if they want their budgets approved.<P>It is time for the Senate to go before the high court and challenge the Palace’s invocation of executive privilege, which is clearly being abused by Gloria Arroyo.<P>The Senate may be taking a risk in that majority of the high court justices are seen to be Gloria’s partisans and protectors, and may again rule in her favor, instead of upholding the principles of congressional power on oversight and investigative functions.<P>But it won’t be too great a risk for the Senate. It would have done its job of challenging executive privilege, and if the Senate loses the case, it will be the high court that will be losing out more, in the end.<P>It would have proved to the Filipino people that it is an adjunct of Malacañang, utterly servile to the executive power.<P><P><P><P><P><P><P><P><P><CENTER><IMG SRC='../../pics/tribbar.jpg'><P><a href='#top'>Back to top</A><P> 
